            "content_license": "CC BY-SA 3.0",
            "score": 2,
            "is_accepted": true,
            "last_activity_date": 1475352451,
            "creation_date": 1475351850,
            "body": "<p>When a number is even the right most bit in its binary representation is <code>0<\/code>. Dividing a number by 2 removes this zero.<\/p>\n\n<pre><code>N = 16       =&gt; 8       =&gt; 4      =&gt; 2     =&gt; 1\n    (10000)2 =&gt; (1000)2 =&gt; (100)2 =&gt; (10)2 =&gt; 1\n<\/code><\/pre>\n\n<p>When a number is odd the right most bit in its binary representation is <code>1<\/code>. The algorithm decerements the number when it receives an odd number. Decrementing an odd number will result in changing the rightmost bit from <code>1<\/code> to <code>0<\/code>. So the number becomes even and the algorithm then divides this number by 2 so the right most bit will be removed.<\/p>\n\n<p>So the worst case of the algorithm happens when binary representation of the number is consist of all <code>1<\/code>s:<\/p>\n\n<pre><code>1111111111111\n<\/code><\/pre>\n\n<p>When this happens what the algorithm does is remove each 1 in two steps<\/p>\n\n<pre><code>1111111111111 decrement it because it is odd\n1111111111110 divide it by two because it even \n111111111111\n<\/code><\/pre>\n\n<p>So in the worst case it takes 2* <em>number of 1s<\/em> to reach to <code>1<\/code>. The <em>number of 1s<\/em> is proportionate to log<sub>2<\/sub>N. So the algorithm belongs to <em>O(logN)<\/em>.<\/p>\n",
            "answer_id": 39810903,
            "question_id": 39810561,
            "last_edit_date": 1475352451
        },
        {
            "owner": {
                "profile_image": "https://i.sstatic.net/lIlqX.jpg?s=256",
                "account_id": 3725059,
                "user_type": "registered",
                "user_id": 3169556,
                "link": "https://stackoverflow.com/users/3169556/v78",
